00:17:17,480 --> 00:17:32,600
There's that amazing scene set in the emperor's garden. It's Kunal, the current emperor, is pruning flowers. And he uses this very elegant metaphor, comparing the empire to a garden. He says it needs careful pruning to grow strong.

203
00:17:32,600 --> 00:17:46,520
A beautiful image. But Mike Azuma is not impressed by poetry. He counters by warning that predictability erodes deterrence. If the enemy city-state knows for a fact that you aren't going to burn their city to the ground,

204
00:17:46,520 --> 00:17:54,640
if they know you're just going to show up, capture a few of their guys, and then go home until next season, why should they continue to pay tribute? Why should they submit?

205
00:17:54,880 --> 00:17:59,680
What's their incentive to obey, other than, you know, a bit of inconvenience once a year?

206
00:18:00,100 --> 00:18:09,280
It's a very valid critique. Kalakalel thinks he's building sustainability and control. Moctezuma looks at the same system and thinks he's building a trap for themselves.

207
00:18:09,280 --> 00:18:19,180
He believes that without the genuine, credible threat of total destruction held in reserve, the tributary states will eventually get brave and revolt.

208
00:18:19,180 --> 00:18:30,980
And then you've got Tizok, the high priest. He adds this whole other layer of skepticism from a completely different angle. He's not worried about military deterrence. He's worried about faith.

209
00:18:30,980 --> 00:18:38,780
Yes. He has that line that, I mean, it gave me chills. He warns that ritual without danger becomes theater.

210
00:18:39,140 --> 00:18:41,060
Ritual without danger becomes theater.

211
00:18:41,340 --> 00:18:50,600
Oof. He's saying that if the war gets too clean, if it gets too choreographed and safe, the gods won't respect it. And more importantly, the people won't respect it.

212
00:18:50,760 --> 00:18:54,180
It just becomes a performance, a pageant.

213
00:18:54,260 --> 00:18:56,660
And performances don't hold empires together.

214
00:18:56,660 --> 00:19:11,260
No. He believes the universe demands entropy. It demands real blood, real risk, real chaos. If you try to sanitize it too much, if you try to make it too neat, the system loses its metaphysical weight. It becomes hollow.

215
00:19:11,500 --> 00:19:25,400
So you have these high-level debates happening in the halls of power. The engineer, the general, the priest. But while they're all arguing philosophy, the system itself is actually running on the backs of people like Jochitl.

216
00:19:25,400 --> 00:19:32,440
Jochitl, the runner. I feel like she's the unsung hero of this whole story, honestly. She's the embodiment of the system's infrastructure.

217
00:19:32,660 --> 00:19:36,340
She's the one actually making it work on the ground, day in and day out.

218
00:19:36,640 --> 00:19:41,520
The essay describes her and the other runners as the vector field.

219
00:19:42,640 --> 00:19:47,280
She is the infrastructure. She's not a general or a priest with grand theories.

220
00:19:47,840 --> 00:19:53,620
She is the one carrying the messages. She's the fiber-optic cable of the Triple Alliance.

221
00:19:53,620 --> 00:19:59,480
And she carries the death whistle. Which, I have to say, that detail in the screenplay was fascinating.

222
00:19:59,880 --> 00:20:06,960
It's an incredible reinterpretation. We usually think of the Aztec death whistle as this ultimate instrument of psychological terror, right?

223
00:20:07,400 --> 00:20:11,400
It's a ceramic skull that makes it sound like a human screaming in agony.

224
00:20:11,560 --> 00:20:16,600
Right. It's the sound of nightmares. You hear that sound on the battlefield and your blood runs cold. You freeze.

225
00:20:16,600 --> 00:20:25,920
But in Talaquil's engineered system, it's repurposed. It's given a new job. It becomes a boundary marker. It's the referee's whistle.

226
00:20:26,820 --> 00:20:32,420
A specific series of blasts signals the start of the engagement and another signals the end.

227
00:20:32,760 --> 00:20:39,980
That is such a huge shift in meaning. It takes the most terrifying sound imaginable and turns it into a tool of order.

228
00:20:39,980 --> 00:20:45,460
It goes from, I am coming to kill you, to game on and game off.

229
00:20:45,800 --> 00:20:49,300
It really shows how communication is more durable than stone.

230
00:20:50,020 --> 00:20:54,760
The essay makes this point that even when the councils are deadlocked in debate,

231
00:20:55,240 --> 00:21:00,440
even when the policy is failing at the highest levels, the runners keep running. The vectors persist.

232
00:21:00,960 --> 00:21:04,200
Chichita's the glue holding this whole fragile agreement together.

233
00:21:04,200 --> 00:21:08,940
She is the one making sure that Tlaxcowians know the schedule for next month's war.

234
00:21:09,280 --> 00:21:13,020
If she fails, if the message doesn't get through, the whole phase lock falls apart.

235
00:21:13,180 --> 00:21:16,340
And then you have the warriors themselves, the grunts on the ground.

236
00:21:16,440 --> 00:21:19,520
There's that character in the compendium, Yaconex, a young recruit.

237
00:21:20,000 --> 00:21:22,400
He has to learn a whole new grammar of war.

238
00:21:22,820 --> 00:21:26,100
Aspect relegation. That's the term the essay uses for what he's going through.

239
00:21:26,380 --> 00:21:27,960
It's a psychological concept.

240
00:21:27,960 --> 00:21:36,020
Yaconex has to train his own mind, his own reflexes, to say, I capture instead of, I kill.

241
00:21:36,440 --> 00:21:39,940
Which sounds simple when you say it, but in the heat of battle.

242
00:21:40,260 --> 00:21:46,500
When your adrenaline is pumping and someone is swinging an obsidian-bladed club at your head,

243
00:21:46,980 --> 00:21:50,920
that's rewiring your most basic survival instincts.

244
00:21:51,280 --> 00:21:54,480
It is. The instinct is to end the threat permanently.

245
00:21:54,480 --> 00:22:00,360
Yeah. He has to suppress that urge and replace it with a much more complex, much more difficult action.

246
00:22:00,600 --> 00:22:03,800
So he's got to relegate that killing aspect to the background.

247
00:22:03,960 --> 00:22:09,160
Exactly. And the essay argues that this relegation, when practiced by a whole generation of warriors,

248
00:22:09,660 --> 00:22:11,820
creates a profound psychological shift.

249
00:22:12,400 --> 00:22:15,700
The violence gets compressed into habit. It gets ritualized.

250
00:22:16,040 --> 00:22:19,980
The warriors stop seeing it as extraordinary mercy or a strange new rule.

251
00:22:20,340 --> 00:22:24,200
They just see it as the job. This is how war is done. It becomes normal.

252
00:22:24,200 --> 00:22:28,940
But that compression, that normalization, it creates a blind spot, doesn't it?

253
00:22:28,940 --> 00:22:29,720
A huge blind spot.

254
00:22:30,040 --> 00:22:38,100
If you get too used to the compressed version of violence, the ritual, the rules, the whistles, the relative safety,

255
00:22:38,660 --> 00:22:44,620
you might forget what actual, unconstrained, high-resolution violence looks like.

256
00:22:44,880 --> 00:22:48,060
You might forget that not everyone in the world plays by your rules.

257
00:22:48,060 --> 00:22:54,440
You might forget that outside the carefully tended garden of your system, the jungle is still wild.

258
00:22:54,580 --> 00:22:57,600
And that that is the perfect setup for the disaster.

259
00:22:58,100 --> 00:22:58,620
Part four.

260
00:22:59,660 --> 00:23:01,220
The out-of-context problem.

261
00:23:01,600 --> 00:23:02,560
The system crash.

262
00:23:02,740 --> 00:23:04,000
The arrival of the Spanish.

263
00:23:04,220 --> 00:23:08,520
Now, this is one of the most famous stories in history, but the way these documents frame it,

264
00:23:08,720 --> 00:23:11,080
it's completely different from anything I've ever read before.

265
00:23:11,080 --> 00:23:13,800
It's fascinating. Usually this story is told as the conquest.

266
00:23:14,540 --> 00:23:16,700
It's a story of guns, germs, and steel.

267
00:23:17,180 --> 00:23:22,460
It's Cortez, the brilliant conquistador, versus Moctezuma, the doomed emperor.

268
00:23:22,900 --> 00:23:27,460
It's a clash of civilizations, usually framed as advanced versus primitive.

269
00:23:27,600 --> 00:23:28,780
Right, a morality play.

270
00:23:29,120 --> 00:23:31,780
But the source material explicitly avoids that.

271
00:23:31,920 --> 00:23:36,000
It doesn't frame this as good versus evil or even really strength versus weakness.

272
00:23:36,000 --> 00:23:38,660
It frames it as a protocol mismatch.

273
00:23:39,160 --> 00:23:40,000
A protocol mismatch.

274
00:23:40,740 --> 00:23:41,460
I love that term.

275
00:23:41,700 --> 00:23:44,140
It's like trying to plug a USB drive into a toaster.

276
00:23:45,060 --> 00:23:45,320
Yeah.

277
00:23:45,720 --> 00:23:46,540
It doesn't compute.

278
00:23:46,880 --> 00:23:49,380
The two systems are fundamentally incompatible.

279
00:23:49,860 --> 00:23:53,580
The Spanish are described in the essay as an outside context problem.

280
00:23:54,340 --> 00:23:57,760
They are a variable that Tlacalel's system was never designed to handle.

281
00:23:57,960 --> 00:24:00,440
They simply do not recognize the field.

282
00:24:00,860 --> 00:24:02,920
There's that powerful scene on the coast.

283
00:24:02,920 --> 00:24:06,180
So Chiddle, the runner, is the first to see them.

284
00:24:06,380 --> 00:24:07,300
She runs to the beach.

285
00:24:07,700 --> 00:24:09,720
She sees the ships like floating mountains.

286
00:24:10,080 --> 00:24:11,960
She sees the men in metal.

287
00:24:12,340 --> 00:24:14,760
She sees the horses, which are like giant deer.

288
00:24:15,240 --> 00:24:17,780
And she's waiting for something.

289
00:24:18,620 --> 00:24:19,180
A signal.

290
00:24:19,700 --> 00:24:20,260
A banner.

291
00:24:20,620 --> 00:24:21,220
A drum.

292
00:24:21,880 --> 00:24:23,260
A declaration of intent.

293
00:24:23,620 --> 00:24:25,040
She's waiting for the handshake.

294
00:24:25,160 --> 00:24:26,640
She's waiting for the protocol to begin.

295
00:24:26,920 --> 00:24:30,060
She's looking for someone to tell her the time and place for the flower war.

296
00:24:30,620 --> 00:24:31,520
And it never comes.

297
00:24:31,520 --> 00:24:34,880
The essay says the Spanish short-circuit the system.

298
00:24:35,320 --> 00:24:37,560
They operate completely outside the commit boundaries.

299
00:24:37,760 --> 00:24:38,800
They don't wait for the whistle.

300
00:24:39,100 --> 00:24:40,360
They don't care about the calendar.

301
00:24:40,940 --> 00:24:44,000
And they definitely do not care about capturing people alive.

302
00:24:44,400 --> 00:24:46,500
The Chiddle has that heartbreaking line.

303
00:24:47,000 --> 00:24:48,920
She observes them and reports back,

304
00:24:49,500 --> 00:24:50,580
they do not wait.

305
00:24:50,700 --> 00:24:51,640
They do not mirror.

306
00:24:52,060 --> 00:24:53,600
And in that one sentence,

307
00:24:54,020 --> 00:24:56,960
she understands that the entire language of war

308
00:24:56,960 --> 00:25:00,140
she has known her whole life is useless here.

309
00:25:00,140 --> 00:25:03,400
And this is what the sources call the tragedy of compatibility.

310
00:25:03,400 --> 00:25:05,660
Tlaxcalo's system,

311
00:25:05,960 --> 00:25:07,260
for all its brilliance,

312
00:25:07,580 --> 00:25:09,880
relied entirely on mutual recognition.

313
00:25:10,520 --> 00:25:12,900
It worked with their traditional enemies,

314
00:25:13,100 --> 00:25:13,920
the Tlaxcans,

315
00:25:14,180 --> 00:25:16,340
because the Tlaxcans agreed to play.

316
00:25:16,560 --> 00:25:17,800
They hated the Mexicans, sure,

317
00:25:17,960 --> 00:25:19,960
but they agreed on the format of the hatred.

318
00:25:20,340 --> 00:25:21,920
They agreed on the rules of the game.

319
00:25:21,920 --> 00:25:25,080
It's like, imagine two master chess players.

320
00:25:25,440 --> 00:25:26,940
They might despise each other personally,

321
00:25:27,080 --> 00:25:29,520
but they both agree on how the knight moves,

322
00:25:29,660 --> 00:25:30,720
how the bishop moves,

323
00:25:30,960 --> 00:25:32,080
the Spanish show up,

324
00:25:32,100 --> 00:25:33,140
and they don't play chess.

325
00:25:33,240 --> 00:25:34,500
They flip the board over,

326
00:25:34,620 --> 00:25:35,360
shoot the other player,

327
00:25:35,480 --> 00:25:36,740
and set the table on fire.

328
00:25:36,900 --> 00:25:37,740
A perfect analogy.

329
00:25:38,160 --> 00:25:40,560
And because the Mexicans system is so specialized

330
00:25:40,560 --> 00:25:43,520
and so finely tuned to this one specific game,

331
00:25:43,840 --> 00:25:45,980
it doesn't just fail gracefully.

332
00:25:46,140 --> 00:25:46,980
It doesn't bend.

333
00:25:47,220 --> 00:25:48,060
It shatters.

334
00:25:48,260 --> 00:25:49,680
It collapses instantly.

335
00:25:49,680 --> 00:25:52,560
The essay calls it a failure of relegation.

336
00:25:53,200 --> 00:25:54,520
All that violent impulse

337
00:25:54,520 --> 00:25:57,000
the Mexico warriors had trained themselves to suppress.

338
00:25:57,220 --> 00:25:58,820
They can't just switch it back on overnight.

339
00:25:59,160 --> 00:26:00,760
No, and the Spanish violence is.

340
00:26:00,920 --> 00:26:02,180
It's high resolution.

341
00:26:02,580 --> 00:26:03,420
It's uncompressed.

342
00:26:03,880 --> 00:26:06,540
It's raw, chaotic, efficient killing.

343
00:26:07,040 --> 00:26:08,400
It has no ritual attached,

344
00:26:08,580 --> 00:26:12,000
and it completely shocks the Mexica system.

345
00:26:12,300 --> 00:26:13,320
And the Mexico warriors,

346
00:26:13,520 --> 00:26:16,680
who have spent a generation training to not kill,

347
00:26:16,820 --> 00:26:17,920
to aim for the limbs,

348
00:26:18,040 --> 00:26:19,120
to listen for the signal,

349
00:26:19,120 --> 00:26:20,380
to work as a team,

350
00:26:20,460 --> 00:26:22,640
to capture, not annihilate,

351
00:26:23,120 --> 00:26:27,320
they are completely cognitively unprepared for this.

352
00:26:27,440 --> 00:26:29,460
It's a cognitive shock more than anything else.

353
00:26:29,860 --> 00:26:30,840
They're looking for the rules,

354
00:26:30,960 --> 00:26:31,740
and there are none.

355
00:26:32,320 --> 00:26:34,260
Talakalo's beautiful architecture,

356
00:26:34,480 --> 00:26:35,720
his carefully constructed,

357
00:26:36,260 --> 00:26:38,780
phase-locked sine wave of violence.

358
00:26:39,040 --> 00:26:40,040
It meets a tsunami.

359
00:26:40,540 --> 00:26:41,260
And a sine wave,

360
00:26:41,340 --> 00:26:42,040
no matter how elegant,

361
00:26:42,220 --> 00:26:43,380
cannot stop a tsunami.

362
00:26:43,560 --> 00:26:44,880
It's a complete systems failure.

363
00:26:45,060 --> 00:26:46,980
So the system crashes hard.

364
00:26:46,980 --> 00:26:48,800
The flower wars end,

365
00:26:48,980 --> 00:26:49,760
not with a treaty,

366
00:26:49,900 --> 00:26:51,800
but with a horrifying reality check.

367
00:26:52,320 --> 00:26:55,180
The screenplay has these scenes of just utter chaos.

368
00:26:56,180 --> 00:26:57,400
Moctezuma, now emperor,

369
00:26:57,620 --> 00:26:59,260
tries to go back to the old ways,

370
00:26:59,360 --> 00:27:00,960
to unleash unrestricted force,

371
00:27:01,240 --> 00:27:02,120
but it's too late.

372
00:27:02,580 --> 00:27:03,620
The rhythm is broken.

373
00:27:04,160 --> 00:27:05,580
The muscle memory is gone.

374
00:27:05,580 --> 00:27:07,200
And Tezok, the priest,

375
00:27:07,600 --> 00:27:10,720
he reacts the way feeling systems so often do.

376
00:27:11,180 --> 00:27:13,800
He panics and tries to escalate the old solution.

377
00:27:14,280 --> 00:27:16,380
He dramatically increases the sacrifices.

378
00:27:16,760 --> 00:27:17,620
His logic is,

379
00:27:18,440 --> 00:27:19,760
if the system isn't working,

380
00:27:19,900 --> 00:27:22,020
it must be because we're not doing it harder.

381
00:27:22,520 --> 00:27:23,620
Which is so tragic.

382
00:27:23,780 --> 00:27:25,840
It's mistaking volume for control.

383
00:27:26,080 --> 00:27:26,440
It's just,

384
00:27:26,580 --> 00:27:28,660
it's the desperate act of a man

385
00:27:28,660 --> 00:27:30,960
who sees the universe he understood falling apart

386
00:27:30,960 --> 00:27:32,540
and thinks he can fix it

387
00:27:32,540 --> 00:27:34,460
by shouting louder at the gods.

388
00:27:34,460 --> 00:27:35,380
It's panic.

389
00:27:36,060 --> 00:27:36,500
But,

390
00:27:36,780 --> 00:27:38,360
and this is where this deep dug

391
00:27:38,360 --> 00:27:39,480
gets really profound for me,

392
00:27:40,060 --> 00:27:41,680
the story in these documents

393
00:27:41,680 --> 00:27:43,700
doesn't just end with the crash.

394
00:27:43,900 --> 00:27:45,520
It doesn't end with the fall of the city.

395
00:27:45,680 --> 00:27:45,840
No.

396
00:27:46,300 --> 00:27:46,880
Part five,

397
00:27:47,500 --> 00:27:48,820
irreversibility in memory.

398
00:27:49,860 --> 00:27:51,140
This is where the source material just,

399
00:27:51,300 --> 00:27:52,620
it elevates the entire narrative.

400
00:27:52,800 --> 00:27:53,580
It asks the question,

401
00:27:54,440 --> 00:27:56,320
what happens after the end of your world?

402
00:27:56,820 --> 00:27:58,020
What survives the crash?

403
00:27:58,260 --> 00:28:00,060
And the essay introduces another concept

404
00:28:00,060 --> 00:28:00,920
from computer science,

405
00:28:01,380 --> 00:28:03,120
event-sourced civilization.

406
00:28:03,120 --> 00:28:04,600
What does that even mean?

407
00:28:04,820 --> 00:28:06,420
It's a way of thinking about data.

408
00:28:07,280 --> 00:28:08,860
In an event-sourced system,

409
00:28:09,080 --> 00:28:11,560
the truth isn't just the current state of things,

410
00:28:11,560 --> 00:28:13,160
like the balance in your bank account.

411
00:28:13,680 --> 00:28:16,020
The truth is the complete,

412
00:28:16,340 --> 00:28:19,260
unchangeable log of every transaction

413
00:28:19,260 --> 00:28:20,400
that ever happened.

414
00:28:20,640 --> 00:28:21,760
The whole ledger.

415
00:28:21,840 --> 00:28:22,740
The ledger, right.

416
00:28:22,860 --> 00:28:23,740
And Tlachalel,

417
00:28:23,880 --> 00:28:24,860
from the very beginning,

418
00:28:24,960 --> 00:28:26,040
was always counting.

419
00:28:26,440 --> 00:28:27,380
Remember scene one,

420
00:28:27,760 --> 00:28:28,700
counting the stones?

421
00:28:29,000 --> 00:28:30,100
He was a record keeper.

422
00:28:30,100 --> 00:28:31,980
The flower wars,

423
00:28:32,080 --> 00:28:32,440
in a way,

424
00:28:32,520 --> 00:28:34,540
were a method to log violence,

425
00:28:34,800 --> 00:28:36,540
to keep a meticulous record,

426
00:28:36,620 --> 00:28:36,880
to say,

427
00:28:37,060 --> 00:28:38,720
this happened at this time

428
00:28:38,720 --> 00:28:39,440
with these people,

429
00:28:39,600 --> 00:28:40,980
and this was the result.

430
00:28:41,100 --> 00:28:42,640
It was a living ledger

431
00:28:42,640 --> 00:28:43,860
of the empire's power.

432
00:28:44,060 --> 00:28:44,300
Yes.

433
00:28:44,760 --> 00:28:46,220
And when the Spanish arrive

434
00:28:46,220 --> 00:28:47,800
and the whole system crashes,

435
00:28:48,340 --> 00:28:48,880
Tlachalel,

436
00:28:49,080 --> 00:28:50,000
now an old man,

437
00:28:50,400 --> 00:28:51,700
has this final,

438
00:28:52,100 --> 00:28:52,920
brilliant insight.

439
00:28:53,380 --> 00:28:55,080
He realizes he can't save the government.

440
00:28:55,080 --> 00:28:56,460
He can't save the empire.

441
00:28:56,680 --> 00:28:58,340
He can't save the current state.

442
00:28:58,560 --> 00:28:59,160
It's over.

443
00:28:59,360 --> 00:29:00,380
But he can save the log.

444
00:29:00,520 --> 00:29:01,580
He can save the memory.

445
00:29:01,880 --> 00:29:03,020
He can preserve the ledger.

446
00:29:03,220 --> 00:29:03,740
He pivots.

447
00:29:03,940 --> 00:29:05,600
He changes his role one last time.

448
00:29:05,780 --> 00:29:07,740
He stops being the architect of the system

449
00:29:07,740 --> 00:29:09,840
and becomes the teacher of its memory.

450
00:29:10,060 --> 00:29:11,300
There's that incredible scene

451
00:29:11,300 --> 00:29:12,060
in the screenplay,

452
00:29:12,180 --> 00:29:13,120
late in the story.

453
00:29:13,760 --> 00:29:15,760
The city is in ruins.

